s, provided a crucial strategy in social organization. Drawing on ethnographic and archaeological data and evolutionary, economic, and anthropological theory, he shows that these small groups devised diverse solutions to environmental, technological, and social obstacles to the intensified use of resources. This book revises our understanding of how California became the most densely populated landscape in aboriginal North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndians of North AmericazCaliforniaxCivilization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aaboriginal california.  aaboriginal north america.  aamerican empire.  aamerican history.  aarchaeology.  acalifornia.  aconflict.  acultural adaptation.  adiverse solutions.  adiversity.  aeconomic theory.  aethnographic research.  aevolutionary theory.  ahardship.  ahistory.  aindigenous cultures.  aindigenous peoples.  ainterdisciplinary.  anative americans.  aorderly anarchy.  aorigins of human behavior and culture series.  apower struggle.  aprehistoric languages.  arealistic.  aretrospective.  asocial complexity.  asocial organization.  asociopolitical evolution.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028333640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095919440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959194423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959194/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY